data.content:
This is a **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. Here's what happened:

**The problem:** C# 14 introduces new built-in span conversions. When you write `array.Contains(num)` inside an expression tree, the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Since `MemoryExtensions.Contains` cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree, it throws at runtime.

**Fix options** — force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
(array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
(array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
(array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these will restore the .NET 9 behavior. The same issue can affect `Reverse()` on arrays (now binds to the in-place `Span` version), so audit for similar patterns.
